The structural hole theory provides a novel perspective for understanding the local performance of individuals. In fact, a structural hole is a gap between two unconnected nodes. When these two unconnected nodes are connected by a third node, the bridging node usually has more information advantages and control advantages since it acts as a mediator between different nodes. In order to quantify the control advantage of bridging nodes, Burt introduced the network constraint coefficient (NCC). The NCC for ith node is described as the following:6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
